Data science challenge

The competition will take place in the Data Science Challenges platform, which is available at the following link:

https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it

You must log in with your credentials to enter the competition. There, you will find a copy of the training and test datasets. However, a copy of the data is also available on the github repository and can be downloaded using the code provided in this notebook.

Assignment rules and evaluation criteria

The dataset contains information about bookings made at a resort hotel. Please refer to the former assignment for a detailed description of each variable.

In this version of the dataset, there is a new variable (response) that indicates whether a booking was canceled (response = 2) or not (response = 1). On the other hand, the variables LeadTime and ArrivalDateDayOfMonth have been removed.

Your goal is to predict the response variable using the variables at your disposal.

Note

When tidying the data, many of you noticed that there are duplicated entries. According to the original source, these are legitimate bookings with identical covariates. For the sake of this assignment, let us trust the source. In any event, some of these “duplicated” bookings were canceled, while others were not.

Submissions are evaluated using the 1 - accuracy, that is, the average error between the predicted response and the observed target (response), that is

\[ \text{average error} = 1 - \text{accuracy} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \mathbb{I}(y_i \neq \hat{y}_i). \]

Warning

The training, public, and private datasets correspond to roughly 67%, 10%, and 23% of the original data, respectively. These subsets have not been randomly sampled. Indeed, the training set related to data point of 2015 and 2016, whereas you will be evaluated on data of 2017!

You are allowed to use methodologies and predictive algorithms that have not been presented in class. However, if you do so, you must be able to explain them in the report and, potentially, in class.

You are not allowed to use any external data, including the data from the previous assignment.

In this competition, you will be evaluated based on:

  • A .pdf report (at most three pages) that you will need to enclose in the data competition platform before the deadline;

  • The final accuracy score on the test set. Please note that only the last submission is evaluated.

The winning teams will present their work in class.

Import the data

You can download the data from the https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it platform or use the following code.

# Import basic libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
# The training dataset comprises 26881 rows and 19 columns
bookings = pd.read_csv("https://datasciencebocconi.github.io/Data/hotels_train.csv")

# The prediction dataset comprises 13179 rows and 18 columns (the label `response` is not available)
bookings_pred = pd.read_csv("https://datasciencebocconi.github.io/Data/hotels_test.csv")

Let us now create a simple predictive model that will serve as benchmark.

Submit a prediction

We implement a simple model (logistic regression model) to illustrate how to submit your prediction.

# Consider here a couple of variables variable
X = bookings[['ADR', 'RequiredCarParkingSpaces']]
X_pred  = bookings_pred[['ADR', 'RequiredCarParkingSpaces']]

# Here, we create the numeric outcome
y = bookings["response"]
# Import a naive Bayes function
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Fit a logistic regression
m_logistic = LogisticRegression(penalty = None, max_iter = 10000)
m_logistic.fit(X, y)

# Predict values on the prediction set
y_logistic_pred = m_logistic.predict(X_pred)
y_logistic_pred
array([1, 1, 1, ..., 1, 1, 1])

Once we obtain a vector of numeric values based on the test set, we must save the vector into a .txt file.

export_pred = pd.DataFrame(y_logistic_pred, columns = ['response'])

# The header and the index are removed as this is required by the platform
export_pred.to_csv('logistic_pred.txt', index = False, header = False)

Look for the logistic_pred.txt file created on your computer, or download it from Google Colab. Of course, you can name the file as you wish, perhaps with a name that reminds you of the chosen method.

Then, you can upload the file to the platform https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it and see how you scored on the partial leaderboard.

Let the challenge begin!
